    <title>Combined summary - [Bitcoin Advent Calendar] Decentralized Coordination Free Mining Pools</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T03:37:23.945310+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2021-December/019702.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The discussion revolves around various proposals related to Bitcoin mining pools, including a proposal to decrease the size of minimum viable pool through sub-block pooling. This proposed system is similar to Monero's implementation of their version of p2pool, which allows for viable solo mining. However, concerns have been raised about whether this design can enable solo mining or not. Additionally, there is a debate on the viability of payment pools to cut-through chain space and whether strongly online counterparties would be able to coordinate more efficiently or not.Another proposal involves creating a separate blockchain called "superblocks" that would progress linearly and keep block headers instead of transactions. One concern raised is the safety of throwing block rewards into a channel and being able to spend them immediately, which could be solved by reducing the on-chain wait time for spending block rewards instead. There are also discussions about the role of Proof of Stake and the value of signing in mining. Some individuals suggest that CheckTemplateVerify (CTV) should focus on one problem for which it's demonstrably the right and best solution instead of trying to be all things to all people.Braidpool is a new mining pool coordination system that aims to increase payout regularity and lower the viable size of mining pools. The proposal uses multisig and leaf nodes to enable smaller miners to participate without central custody, but the issue of data availability remains. There are many different approaches to achieving the goal of decentralizing mining, and each proposal has its own benefits and limitations that need to be carefully considered.Overall, the discussion demonstrates ongoing debates among Bitcoin developers about how to improve mining pool efficiency and security, exploring different designs and techniques while considering all aspects of each proposal. The proposals aim to increase payout regularity, lower on-chain footprint, and alleviate centralization pressures usually faced by pools. However, some suggest that the proposals need to focus on one problem for which a proposed solution is demonstrably the right and best solution. It is important to consider the trade-offs and risks associated with each proposal and avoid oversimplification.</summary>
